const LESSON_SECTIONS = [
  { title: "1. Why Illumina is a different array logic", intro: "The professor changes technology again: after Stanford spotting and Affymetrix photolithography, Illumina uses pre-made oligonucleotide-coated beads assembled into a BeadChip.", slides: [
    { img: "title", title: "Where this lesson sits", body: "This remains a theoretical Module 1 lesson, but it prepares the methylation dataset logic used later in Module 2." },
    { img: "illuminaHq", title: "Illumina: arrays plus sequencing", body: "Illumina competed with Affymetrix in arrays, but the professor stresses that the company evolved strongly toward next-generation sequencing." },
    { img: "beadHistory", title: "A bead is a local probe factory", body: "Each bead carries many copies of a specific oligonucleotide. The array is therefore assembled from beads rather than synthesized directly in place." },
    { img: "beadPits", title: "Pits, beads, redundancy and decoding", body: "The chip contains microwells/pits that hold beads. Because bead identities must be known after random assembly, Illumina uses an optical decoding/addressing phase.", professor: "She contrasts this with previous manufacturing strategies: competitive arrays use spotting; Affymetrix uses in situ photolithography; Illumina uses pre-made beads assembled into pits." }
  ]},
  { title: "2. From transcriptome arrays to DNA methylation", intro: "Old transcriptome BeadArrays are shown mainly to explain the bead concept. The lecture then pivots to DNA methylation, the topic that matters for the methylation-array dataset.", slides: [
    { img: "transcriptome", title: "Transcriptome BeadChips as background", body: "The transcriptome format helps understand beads and barcoding, but the professor explicitly says the course focus is DNA methylation." },
    { img: "methylationWhy", title: "Methylation connects exposome and gene expression", body: "Physiological, pathological and environmental stimuli can act through epigenetic mechanisms, including DNA methylation, chromatin remodeling and non-coding RNAs." },
    { img: "cytosine", title: "CpG methylation in mammalian cells", body: "CpG cytosines can be methylated at carbon 5 of the pyrimidine ring. DNMTs and TET enzymes make methylation a dynamic, regulated state rather than a permanent yes/no property." }
  ], extra: "fraction" },
  { title: "3. Beta values are biological averages, not tissue maps", intro: "Before the chemistry, the professor insists on a conceptual trap: with a pool of cells, methylation is not simply yes/no. The same percentage can hide very different original cell distributions.", slides: [
    { img: "percent", title: "0%, 50%, 100% and intermediate methylation", body: "Counting methylated cytosines across many DNA molecules gives a percentage. This is why array output is quantitative rather than a binary state." },
    { img: "tissue", title: "Same beta, different underlying tissue", body: "Two tissues can have the same overall methylation percentage even when the cell-level pattern is different.", professor: "This is one of the strongest interpretation warnings in the class: do not infer the original tissue architecture from a single beta value.", exam: { question: "Possible question: biologically, what does an intermediate beta value mean?", include: ["State that beta is a quantitative methylation level for a specific CpG in a sample.", "Explain that the sample is a pool of DNA molecules/cells, so intermediate values reflect mixed methylated and unmethylated molecules.", "Add the caveat that the same beta can arise from different underlying tissue or cell distributions."], trap: "Do not say beta = 0.5 means every cell is half methylated. A single CpG molecule is read as C-like or T-like after conversion; the beta is an aggregate signal.", answer: "An intermediate beta value means that, for that CpG in that sample, the methylated signal and unmethylated signal are both present. Biologically this usually reflects a pool of DNA molecules or cell types: some molecules carry the methylated state and others the unmethylated state. It does not tell us the exact tissue architecture, because two different cellular distributions can produce the same average beta." } },
    { img: "cpgContext", title: "Island, shore, shelf and open sea", body: "CpGs are interpreted by genomic context. Shores can be highly informative for gene expression, but the lecture warns that methylation-expression correlation is not automatic." }
  ]},
  { title: "4. Platform evolution: 27K → 450K → EPIC", intro: "Array design follows biological knowledge: new arrays add CpGs when large projects identify new informative regulatory regions.", slides: [
    { img: "platforms", title: "27K and 450K", body: "27K interrogated a small subset of CpGs. 450K greatly expanded coverage and is the reference platform for the Module 2 dataset." },
    { img: "cpgDistribution", title: "What the 450K covers", body: "The 450K platform distributes probes across promoters, gene bodies, UTRs, intergenic loci and CpG island-related categories." },
    { img: "epic1", title: "EPIC version 1", body: "EPIC increased coverage to more than 850K sites and preserved most 450K CpGs, allowing comparison with older datasets." },
    { img: "epic2", title: "EPIC version 2", body: "EPIC v2 approaches one million sites and adds regions informed by cancer, stem-cell and regulatory-genome projects.", professor: "Her take-home idea is not just the number of probes. Arrays improve because biological knowledge improves: FANTOM, ENCODE, cancer projects and chromatin maps suggest new CpGs worth interrogating." }
  ], extra: "platforms" },
  { title: "5. Bisulfite conversion: the essential trick", intro: "PCR alone would erase methylation information. Bisulfite conversion creates a sequence-level memory of whether the original cytosine was methylated or unmethylated.", slides: [
    { img: "prep", title: "Sample preparation workflow", body: "The workflow starts with DNA extraction, then bisulfite conversion, whole-genome amplification, fragmentation and hybridization." },
    { img: "bisulfite", title: "C/T after bisulfite + PCR", body: "Unmethylated C becomes U after bisulfite and T after PCR; methylated C remains read as C. Therefore C means originally methylated and T means originally unmethylated.", professor: "She calls this the trick that makes methylation arrays possible. The exact chemical intermediates are less important than the rule: original unmethylated C → T; original methylated C → C." }
  ], extra: "bisulfite" },
  { title: "6. Infinium I and Infinium II chemistry", intro: "This is the core chemistry and the most exam-like part of the lesson. Both strategies are present in Illumina methylation arrays, but they read methylation differently.", slides: [
    { img: "mainStrategy", title: "Main BeadChip strategy", body: "After bisulfite conversion, the array performs a genotyping-like readout: C near G means originally methylated; T near G means originally unmethylated." },
    { img: "inf1summary", title: "Infinium I: two beads, two probes", body: "Infinium I uses a U bead and an M bead for the same CpG. The two probes are the same except at the informative end." },
    { img: "inf1u", title: "Infinium I unmethylated match", body: "If the converted target has T at the queried site, the U probe can pair correctly and single-base extension produces fluorescence on the U bead." },
    { img: "inf1m", title: "Infinium I methylated match", body: "If the converted target has C at the queried site, the M probe can pair correctly and fluorescence comes from the M bead." },
    { img: "overview", title: "Overview of Infinium I vs II", body: "Infinium I: two beads/probes, where bead identity tells U versus M. Infinium II: one bead/probe, where the added fluorescent nucleotide colour tells U versus M.", professor: "She explicitly says this is a very possible exam question: describe Infinium I and Infinium II strategies for methylated and unmethylated CpG detection.", exam: { question: "Possible question: compare Infinium I and Infinium II chemistry.", include: ["Start from bisulfite conversion: original unmethylated C becomes T, original methylated C stays C.", "Infinium I: two bead/probe types for the same CpG, U and M; fluorescence is interpreted by bead identity.", "Infinium II: one bead/probe; the next base is interrogated by single-base extension with different colours for A/T versus G/C."], trap: "Do not describe both as simply ‘two colours’. In Infinium I, colour is not the main discriminator because the U and M signals come from different beads; in Infinium II, colour is central because U and M are read on the same bead.", answer: "Both assays start from bisulfite-converted DNA. In Infinium I, the same CpG is represented by two bead/probe types: one compatible with the unmethylated converted sequence and one compatible with the methylated converted sequence. A correct match allows single-base extension and fluorescence from the corresponding bead. In Infinium II, there is one bead and one probe; the probe stops before the CpG and the next nucleotide is added by single-base extension. A red A signal indicates T in the target, hence originally unmethylated C, whereas a green G signal indicates C in the target, hence originally methylated C." } }
  ], extra: "infinium" },
  { title: "7. Beta values and raw data matrix", intro: "After chemistry, the output becomes a matrix: CpG IDs in rows, samples in columns and beta values as quantitative methylation levels.", slides: [
    { img: "inf1read", title: "Reading Infinium I", body: "Methylated and unmethylated intensities come from different beads/probes for the same CpG." },
    { img: "inf2read", title: "Reading Infinium II", body: "Methylated and unmethylated signals come from different colours on the same bead." },
    { img: "beta", title: "Beta value formula", body: "Beta is methylated intensity divided by total methylated plus unmethylated intensity plus a constant, usually 100, to avoid 0/0 errors.", professor: "She stresses that beta values range from 0 to 1 and should be read as levels of methylation, not as p-values or fold changes." },
    { img: "bimodal", title: "Expected bimodal distribution", body: "Beta values often show peaks near 0 and 1, with intermediate values between them. This is a first sanity check of methylation data." }
  ], extra: "beta" },
  { title: "8. Probe-type bias and normalization", intro: "Infinium I and II are different designs, so their distributions and variance may differ. This motivates normalization, but the detailed pipeline is left for Module 2.", slides: [
    { img: "diffs", title: "Infinium I and II differ", body: "The two probe types do not have identical signal behavior. They are different chemistries inside the same array." },
    { img: "bias", title: "Systematic bias between probe types", body: "The professor compares this to earlier bias problems: not the same as Cy3/Cy5, but still a technical consequence of a design decision.", professor: "Her phrase is essentially: every technical decision has a consequence. Here the consequence is probe-type bias and the need to think about normalization." },
    { img: "mvalues", title: "Beta values and M values", body: "Beta values are intuitive but heteroscedastic. M values use a log ratio of methylated/unmethylated signal and can be useful for statistical analysis." },
    { img: "normalization", title: "Normalization overview", body: "Early procedures tried to align Infinium II to Infinium I peaks; later pipelines offer multiple choices that will be compared in Module 2." }
  ], extra: "bias" },
  { title: "9. Biological interpretation and epigenetic clocks", intro: "The final part moves from chemistry to applications: methylation can be related to gene expression, disease, aging and biological clocks.", slides: [
    { img: "dmr", title: "Interpreting regions and differential methylation", body: "Methylated CpGs may be interpreted in relation to islands, shores, shelves, open sea, genes and regulatory regions, but correlation with expression is not automatic." },
    { img: "clock", title: "Epigenetic clocks", body: "Specific CpGs can be used to estimate biological age or age acceleration, linking methylation to aging and disease." },
    { img: "clockDesc", title: "Horvath and GrimAge logic", body: "Horvath-type clocks use selected CpGs to estimate age; GrimAge-like clocks relate methylation signatures to mortality risk." },
    { img: "elovl2", title: "ELOVL2 as an aging marker", body: "The professor highlights ELOVL2 CpGs as a striking example of methylation strongly correlating with chronological age." },
    { img: "ageAlgo", title: "From CpG values to an age algorithm", body: "Clock models combine multiple CpGs to estimate epigenetic age or age acceleration." },
    { img: "consensus", title: "Current clinical consensus", body: "The last slide frames GrimAge/GrimAge2 as strong clinical-age predictors, while reminding us that clocks are model-based biomarkers.", professor: "The application point is not memorizing every clock name. It is understanding how methylation arrays produce CpG-level values that can be assembled into biological-age models." }
  ]}
];

